As a father and grandfather, I know what it is like when our young kids go out and we await their safe return. It is gut wrenching, and sadly, we are constantly reminded why we have so much anxiety when our loved ones leave the house.

My sincere thoughts and prayers go out to this young boy‚Äôs family, friends, and community. This is not normal and we cannot normalize it. This is traumatic and upsetting. We need more than outrage, we need a vision and actionable plans.
Just last month, three 13-year-olds were victims of gun violence. Fortunately, all of them survived. This time, we weren‚Äôt so fortunate.

It was also reported that the 14-year-old victim was in possession of a handgun of his own. That is sad and disturbing and speaks to the volume of this epidemic plaguing our community and young people.

This young boy, likely, would have been in a school building had it not been for this pandemic. However, even while walking home or outside playing, he still would have faced the reality of the gun violence epidemic that we have been experiencing for far too long.
